After the parentheses of almost a decade of great financial success as a consultant and businessman - in which he held among others the role of president of the Supervisory Board of BlackRock Germany, in December 2018 he announced the will to compete for party leadership. Defeated twice, he was elected president of the Cdu in January 2022 and his election was interpreted by national and international public opinion as a profound right-wing turn of the party compared to the positions of previous leaders. Merz has already broken a tabooo in&nbsp;Germany&nbsp; since the post-war period, i.e. the implicit ban on traditional parties of any cooperation with the extreme right, having adopted at the end of January, with the votes of the AfD, a non-binding resolution on the right of asylum.
Despite this move, Cdu's leader insists on excluding any kind of alliance with Alice Weidel's party. One of the slogans of his campaign is "Una&nbsp;Germany &nbsp; of which we can be proud again", in reference to the serious economic conditions facing the country. For Merz, the first cure to solve economic problems is to keep the bureaucracy under control. From the energy point of view, it argues that the decision of the previous government to close the remaining German nuclear power plants in the middle of an energy crisis was a mistake that contributed to the increase in costs. Another point in its programme is the reduction of the energy price of at least five cents per kilowattora, through the lowering of the electricity tax and network charges. On immigration, its plan provides for permanent border controls, asylum seekers' rejections and the introduction of administrative detention for foreign offenders pending expulsion. &nbsp;
